<!--
  Exact rate of variation from approximate rate of variation.
  Rate of variation formulas (polynomial, logarithmic, exponential, trig).
-->

<chapter xml:id="chapter-deriv" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>The derivative function</title>

<section xml:id="section-deriv-intro">
<title>Definition</title>

<p>
Recall that a function is an input-output process.
We think of a quantity function <m>q(t)</m> as taking a time as an input and returning the amount of some quantity at that particular time as its output.
But the process of computing derivative values for a specific quantity function is itself also a function <mdash />
again a specific time is the input,
and then <xref ref="definition-avg-rate-derivative-value" /> can be used to return the instantaneous rate of change at that time (if the limit exists there).
Essentially,
to turn the process of computing derivatives into a function,
we take <xref ref="definition-avg-rate-derivative-value" text="title" /> and replace the specific time <m>t^\ast</m> with a variable time <m>t</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-deriv">
	<title>Derivative function</title>
	<p>
	Given quantity function <m>q(t)</m>,
	the associated <term>derivative function</term> is the function
	<me> q'(t) = \lim_{\change{t} \to 0} \frac{ q(t + \change{t}) - q(t) }{ \change{t} } </me>.
	The domain of <m>q'</m> is the collection of all times where <m>q</m> is differentiable,
	and <m>q'</m> remains undefined at those times where <m>q</m> is not differentiable.
	</p>
</definition>

<paragraphs>
	<title>Notation</title>

	<p>
	We use <m>q'(t)</m> when we want to refer to the derivative function for <m>q</m> in function notation,
	while we use <me>\ddt{q}</me> to represent an input-output formula in <m>t</m> for <m>q'</m>.
	Of course, both of these forms are relative to the initial choice of letter <m>q</m> <mdash />
	if we were dealing with a position function <m>s(t)</m> as our quantity function,
	then we would use <m>s'(t)</m> and <me>\ddt{s}</me> to refer to the derivative.
	In some contexts,
	particularly physics,
	you might see <m>\dot{q}</m> used to representative the derivative function for <m>q(t)</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	It is also common practice in mathematics and other science disciplines to use a <q>bare</q> <m>\opddt</m> as an <term>operator</term> that applies the differentiation process to a function or formula.
	For example,
	notation in the form
	<me> \ddt{t^2} = \text{(some formula)} </me>
	or
	<me> \opddt t^2 = \text{(some formula)} </me>,
	is meant to be read as <q><em>a formula for the derivative function associated to the square function is</em> (some formula).</q>
	Or, more simply,
	<q><em>the derivative of the square function is</em> (some formula)</q> <mdash />
	that is, the symbol <m>\opddt</m> represents the phrase <q><em>the derivative of</em>.</q>
	</p>

</paragraphs>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-deriv-algebraically">
<title>Computing algebraically</title>

<p>
In <xref ref="chapter-avg-rate" />,
we calculated individual derivative values by looking for patterns in average-rate approximations to instantaneous rate at a specific time as <m>\change{t} \to 0</m>.
Now we attempt to calculate <em>all</em> derivative values at once,
using the limit definition with a variable time <m>t</m>.
In this process,
there will be two variables involved:
the input time <m>t</m>,
and the limit variable <m>\change{t}</m>.
<alert>As you compute the limit, regard <m>t</m> as an unknown constant</alert>.
We take <m>\change{t} \to 0</m> for one specific <m>t</m>,
but as we leave <m>t</m> unspecified this will do the work of computing the derivative value <m>q'(t)</m> as a formula in <m>t</m>.
</p>

<p> Here is a basic example of the process. </p>

<example xml:id="example-deriv-parabolic-motion">
	<title>Velocity for parabolic motion</title>

	<p>
	Let's return to the situation from <xref ref="example-avg-rate-from-quantity-model" />,
	where we considered parabolic motion due to gravity:
	<me> h(t) = -5 t^2 + 30 t </me>.
	In that example,
	we computed an average velocity over the time domain <m>1 \le t \le 3</m>.
	We could view that computation as computing a forward difference approximation to the instantaneous velocity at <m>t = 1</m>.
	Now let's compute the instantaneous velocity <em>function</em> for this motion,
	and then evaluate at <m>t = 2</m> to compare.
	</p>

	<p>
	First,
	let's set up the forward/backward difference approximation formula.
	We have
	<md>
		<mrow> h(t + \change{t}) \amp = -5 (t + \change{t})^2 + 30 (t + \change{t}) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = -5 \bbrac{t^2 + 2 t \change{t} + {(\change{t})}^2} + 30 (t + \change{t}) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = -5 t^2 - 10 t \change{t} - 5 {(\change{t})}^2 + 30 t + 30 \change{t} </mrow>
	</md>,
	so that
	<md>
		<mrow> h(t + \change{t}) - h(t) \amp = (\bcancel{-5 t^2} - 10 t \change{t} - 5 {(\change{t})}^2 + \bcancel{30 t} + 30 \change{t}) - (\bcancel{-5 t^2} + \bcancel{30 t}) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = - 10 t \change{t} - 5 {(\change{t})}^2 + 30 \change{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = (- 10 t + 30 - 5 \change{t}) \change{t} </mrow>
	</md>.
	Therefore,
	<md>
		<mrow> \slope{h}{t} \amp = \frac{ h(t + \change{t}) - h(t) }{ \change{t} } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ (- 10 t + 30 - 5 \change{t}) \bcancel{\change{t}} }{ \bcancel{\change{t}} } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = - 10 t + 30 - 5 \change{t} </mrow>
	</md>.
	Taking <m>\change{t} \to 0</m>,
	<me> \slope{h}{t} \to -10 t + 30 \qquad \text{as} \qquad \change{t} \to 0 </me>.
	Therefore, in differential notation we can write
	<me> \ddt{h} = -10 t + 30 </me>,
	or in function notation we can write
	<me> q'(t) = -10 t + 30 </me>.
	</p>

	<p>
	If we wish,
	we can now evaluate
	<me> q'(1) = 20 </me>.
	Comparing that with our average rate computation in <xref ref="example-avg-rate-from-quantity-model" />,
	it's no surprise that our previous average velocity calculation is not a good estimate of the instantaneous velocity,
	as <m>2</m> seconds is too long of a time interval to give a good estimate for this model.
	</p>

</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-deriv-basic-formulas">
<title>Fundamental differentiation formulas and principles</title>

<subsection>
<title>Two fundamental formulas</title>

<p>
Function formulas are built out of the independent variable and constants.
So we'll start by analysing the two simplest possible quantity models built on those two components.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-deriv-constant">
	<title>Derivative of a constant</title>

	<statement><p>
		For any constant <m>c</m>, we have <me> \ddt{c} = 0 </me>.
		That is, <alert>the derivative of a constant is zero</alert>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		Consider quantity function <m>q(t) = c</m>.
		Then also <m>q(t + \change{t}) = c</m>,
		so <me> q(t + \change{t}) - q(t) = c - c = 0 </me>.
		Therefore, <me> \slope{q}{t} = \frac{ q(t + \change{t}) - q(t) }{ \change{t} } = \frac{0}{\change{t}} </me>.
		Considering <m>\change{t} \approx 0</m> but <m>\change{t} \neq 0</m>,
		this always computes to <m>0</m>.
		So, in fact, these average-rate approximations are not approximations but instead they are already the exact value,
		and we have <me>\slope{q}{t} \to 0 \qquad \text{as} \qquad \change{t} \to 0</me>.
		Therefore, for a constant function we have
		<me> \ddt{q} = 0 </me>.
	</p></proof>

</identity>

<identity xml:id="pattern-deriv-var">
	<title>Derivative of the independent variable</title>

	<statement><p> We have <me> \ddt{t} = 1 </me>. </p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		Consider quantity function <m>q(t) = t</m>.
		Then <m>q(t + \change{t}) = t + \change{t}</m>,
		so <me> q(t + \change{t}) - q(t) = (t + \change{t}) - t = \change{t} </me>.
		Therefore,
		<md>
			<mrow> \slope{q}{t} \amp = \frac{ q(t + \change{t}) - q(t) }{ \change{t} } </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{ \change{t} }{ \change{t} } </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = 1 </mrow>
		</md>.
		Again, as this average rate ends up being constant,
		we have <me>\slope{q}{t} \to 1 \qquad \text{as} \qquad \change{t} \to 0</me>,
		and so <me> \ddt{q} = 1 </me>.
	</p></proof>

</identity>

<note><p>
	In the justifications for <xref ref="pattern-deriv-constant" /> and <xref ref="pattern-deriv-var" />
	we are not making the mistake of taking <m>0/0 = 0</m> to be true,
	because in the limit defining <m>q'(t)</m> we think of <m>\change{t} \approx 0</m> but <m>\change{t} \neq 0</m>.
</p></note>


</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Scaling and adding quantities does the same to the derivative</title>

<p> Now we'll work a little more generally to develop two algebraic rules for derivatives. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-deriv-scale">
	<title>Derivative of a scaled quantity</title>

	<statement><p>
		If <m>q(t)</m> is a differentiable quantity function,
		then for any constant <m>c</m> we have <me> \opddt (c q) = c \, \ddt{q} </me>.
		That is, <alert>the derivative of a constant multiple is the constant multiple of the derivative</alert>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		Consider quantity function <m>p(t) = c q(t)</m>.
		Then <me> p(t + \change{t}) = c q(t + \change{t}) </me>,
		so
		<md>
			<mrow> p(t + \change{t}) - p(t) \amp = c q(t + \change{t}) - c q(t) </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = c \bbrac{ q(t + \change{t}) - q(t) } </mrow>
		</md>.
		Therefore,
		<md>
			<mrow> \slope{p}{t} \amp = \frac{ p(t + \change{t}) - p(t) }{ \change{t} } </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{c \bbrac{ q(t + \change{t}) - q(t) } }{ \change{t} } </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = c \, \frac{\bbrac{ q(t + \change{t}) - q(t) } }{ \change{t} } </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = c \, \slope{q}{t} </mrow>
		</md>.
		Since this holds for all <m>\change{t} \approx 0</m> but <m>\change{t} \neq 0</m>,
		and we have <me>\slope{q}{t} \to \ddt{q} \qquad \text{as} \qquad \change{t} \to 0</me>,
		then we must have <me>\slope{p}{t} \to c \, \ddt{q} \qquad \text{as} \qquad \change{t} \to 0</me>.
		Therefore,
		<me> \ddt{p} = c \, \ddt{q} </me>,
		as claimed.
	</p></proof>

</identity>

<figure xml:id="figure-deriv-tangent-v-scale">
	<caption> Scaling a tangent line scales its slope. </caption>
	<image width="50%">
		<description>A tangent to a graph and a scaled tangent to a scaled graph.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="deriv.d/v-scaled-tangent.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
<xref ref="pattern-deriv-h-scale" /> applies equally well when the vertical scale factor is negative.
Thinking in terms of tangent lines,
if we reflect vertically then the rise becomes negative while the run stays the same.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-deriv-tangent-v-reflect">
	<caption> Reflecting a tangent line makes its slope negative. </caption>
	<image width="50%">
		<description>A tangent to a graph and a reflected tangent to a reflected graph.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="deriv.d/v-reflect-tangent.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<example>
	In <xref ref="example-deriv-parabolic-motion" />,
	for <me> h(t) = -5 t^2 + 30 t </me>
	we computed <me> \ddt{h} = -10 t + 30 </me>.
	So if we had
	<md>
		<mrow>
			q(t) \amp = t^2 - 6 t
			\amp \amp\implies \amp
			q(t) \amp = \left(- {1 \over 5}\right) \, h(t)
		</mrow>
	</md>,
	then
	<md>
		<mrow> \ddt{q} \amp = \left(- {1 \over 5}\right) \, \ddt{h} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \left(- {1 \over 5}\right) \, (-10 t + 30) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 2 t - 3 </mrow>
	</md>.
</example>

<identity xml:id="pattern-deriv-sum">
	<title>Derivative of a sum of quantities</title>

	<statement><p>
		If <m>q_1(t)</m> and <m>q_2(t)</m> are differentiable quantity functions,
		then <me>\opddt (q_1 + q_2) = \ddt{q_1} + \ddt{q_2} </me>.
		That is, <alert>the derivative of a sum is the sum of the derivatives</alert>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		Consider quantity function <me>p(t) = q_1(t) + q_2(t)</me>.
		Then <me> p(t + \change{t}) = q_1(t + \change{t}) + q_2(t + \change{t}) </me>,
		so
		<md>
			<mrow> p(t + \change{t}) - p(t) \amp = \bbrac{ q_1(t + \change{t}) + q_2(t + \change{t}) } - \bbrac{ q_1(t) + q_2(t) } </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \bbrac{ q_1(t + \change{t}) - q_1(t) } + \bbrac{ q_2(t + \change{t}) - q_2(t)} </mrow>
		</md>.
		Therefore,
		<md>
			<mrow> \slope{p}{t} \amp = \frac{ p(t + \change{t}) - p(t) }{ \change{t} } </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{ \bbrac{ q_1(t + \change{t}) - q_1(t) } + \bbrac{ q_2(t + \change{t}) - q_2(t)} }{ \change{t} } </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{ \bbrac{ q_1(t + \change{t}) - q_1(t) } }{ \change{t} } + \frac{ \bbrac{ q_2(t + \change{t}) - q_2(t)} }{ \change{t} } </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \slope{q_1}{t} + \slope{q_2}{t} </mrow>
		</md>.
		Since this holds for all <m>\change{t} \approx 0</m> but <m>\change{t} \neq 0</m>,
		and we have <me>\slope{q_1}{t} \to \ddt{q_1}, \quad \slope{q_2}{t} \to \ddt{q_2} \qquad \text{as} \qquad \change{t} \to 0</me>,
		then we must have <me>\slope{p}{t} \to \ddt{q_1} + \ddt{q_2} \qquad \text{as} \qquad \change{t} \to 0</me>.
		Therefore,
		<me> \ddt{p} = \ddt{q_1} + \ddt{q_2} </me>,
		as claimed.
	</p></proof>

</identity>

<example xml:id="example-deriv-linear">
	<title>Derivative of a linear quantity function</title>

	<p>
	For <me> q(t) = r t + q_0 </me>,
	we may apply a combination of our rules and basic formulas so far:
	<md>
		<mrow> \ddt{q} \amp = \opddt (r t + q_0) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \opddt (r t) + \ddt{q_0} \amp \amp\text{(i)} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \opddt (r t) + 0 \amp \amp\text{(ii)} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = r \ddt{t} \amp \amp\text{(iii)} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = r \cdot 1 \amp \amp\text{(iv)} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = r </mrow>
	</md>,
	with step justifications
	<ol label="(i)">
		<li> <xref ref="pattern-deriv-sum" /> </li>
		<li> <xref ref="pattern-deriv-constant" /> </li>
		<li> <xref ref="pattern-deriv-scale" /> </li>
		<li> <xref ref="pattern-deriv-var" />. </li>
	</ol>
	</p>

</example>

<p>
Recall that a function that exhibits a uniformly constant rate is must be linear.
<xref ref="example-deriv-linear" /> says the opposite:
a linear function exhibits a uniformly constant rate.
Graphically, this corresponds to exhibiting a constant slope,
so that an average rate calculation
<me> \slope{q}{t} </me>
between any pair of points on the graph leads to the same result.
(See <xref ref="example-avg-rate-linear-quantity" />,
and <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-secant-on-linear" /> in particular.)
</p>

<p>
By definition,
a tangent line to a quantity's graph meets that graph at a particular point with slope equal to the quantity's derivative value there.
<xref ref="example-deriv-linear" /> shows that the slope of that tangent line will be the same as the slope of the quantity's graph,
so in fact they will be the same line.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-deriv-tangent-to-a-line">
	<title>Tangent to a line</title>
	<p>
	A linear quantity function is differentiable at every input time,
	and the tangent line at every point on the quantity's graph is the same line as the graph itself.
	</p>
</identity>

<p>
Finally,
consider the special case of <xref ref="pattern-deriv-sum" />
where the second function is a constant function:
if <me> q(t) = q_1(t) + c </me>,
then
<md>
	<mrow> \ddt{q} \amp = \opddt (q_1 + c) </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \ddt{q_1} + \ddt{c} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \ddt{q_1} + 0 </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \ddt{q_1} </mrow>
</md>.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-deriv-vertical-shift">
	<title>Derivative of a vertical shift</title>
	<p>
	Suppose quantity functions <m>q_1</m> and <m>q_2</m> are vertical shifts of each other,
	so that there exists a constant <m>c</m> with
	<me> q_2(t) = q_1(t) + c </me>.
	Then the two functions are differentiable at the same input values,
	with <me> \ddt{q_2} = \ddt{q_1} </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<figure xml:id="figure-deriv-tangent-v-shift">
	<caption> Shifting a tangent line does not change its slope. </caption>
	<image width="50%">
		<description>A tangent to a graph and a shifted tangent to a shifted graph.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="deriv.d/v-shifted-tangent.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
Finally,
let's consider the effect of horizontal transformations on derivative.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-deriv-h-shift">
	<title>Derivative of a horizontally-shifted quantity function</title>

	<statement><p>
		If we shift a differentiable quantity function <m>p(t)</m> to create a new function <me> q(t) = p(t - c) </me>,
		then the new function is also differentiable,
		and the associated derivative function is also a shift: <me> q'(t) = p'(t - c) </me>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><title>Justification idea</title>
		<p>
		Instead of carrying out a detailed calculation of <m>dq / dt</m>,
		let's just argue in terms of the concept of the derivative.
		If the value of <m>dq / dt</m> at a particular time <m>t = t_0</m> represents the rate of variation of <m>q</m> at that time,
		but <me> q(t) = p(t - c) </me>,
		then we are really just measuring the rate of variation of <m>p</m> at the <q>earlier</q> time <m>t = t_0 -c</m>.
		</p>
	</proof>

</identity>

<figure xml:id="figure-deriv-tangent-h-shift">
	<caption> Shifting a tangent line does not change its slope. </caption>
	<image width="50%">
		<description>A tangent to a graph and a shifted tangent to a shifted graph.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="deriv.d/h-shifted-tangent.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<identity xml:id="pattern-deriv-h-scale">
	<title>Derivative of a horizontally-scaled quantity function</title>

	<statement><p>
		If we horizontally scale a differentiable quantity function <m>p(t)</m> to create a new function <me> q(t) = p(a t) </me>,
		then the new function is also differentiable,
		and the associated derivative function is also a scaling,
		but both vertically and horizontally by the same factor: <me> q'(t) = a p'(a t) </me>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof>

		<p>
		First let's examine the pattern of average rate calculations for the scaled quantity function:
		<md>

			<mrow> \slope{q}{t} \amp = \frac{q(t_2) - q(t_1)}{t_2 - t_1} </mrow>

			<mrow> \amp = \frac{p(a t_2) - p(a t_1)}{t_2 - t_1} </mrow>

		</md>.
		This almost looks like an average rate calculation for <m>p</m>,
		but the two times in the denominator don't match the times used in the numerator.
		Let's fix that:
		<md>

			<mrow> \slope{q}{t} \amp = \frac{p(a t_2) - p(a t_1)}{t_2 - t_1} \cdot \frac{a}{a} </mrow>

			<mrow> \amp = a \cdot \frac{p(a t_2) - p(a t_1)}{a t_2 - a t_1} </mrow>

		</md>.
		So an average rate calculation for <m>q</m> over domain <m>t_1 \le t \le t_2</m> is a scaling of an average rate calculation for <m>p</m> over domain <m>a t_1 \le t \le a t_2</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="figure-deriv-h-scaled-avg-rate">
			<caption>
				An average rate calculation on one graph stretched into an average rate calculation on another.
				Note that in the case that <m>a \gt 1</m>
				(which is what is pictured here),
				then the graph of <m>q</m> is a <em>compression</em> of the graph of <m>p</m>.
				And notice how this makes the slope of the secant line on the graph of <m>q</m> <em>steeper</em> than the slope of the secant line on the graph of <m>p</m>.
			</caption>

			<sidebyside widths="25% 50%">

				<figure xml:id="figure-deriv-h-scaled-avg-rate-1">
					<caption>
						A secant line representing an average rate on a compressed graph.
					</caption>
					<image>
						<description>
							A secant line representing an average rate on a compressed graph.
						</description>
						<latex-image><xi:include href="deriv.d/h-scaled-avg-rate-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
					</image>
				</figure>

				<figure xml:id="figure-deriv-h-scaled-avg-rate-2">
					<caption>
						A stretched secant line representing an average rate on the original graph.
					</caption>
					<image>
						<description>
							A stretched secant line representing an average rate on the original graph.
						</description>
						<latex-image><xi:include href="deriv.d/h-scaled-avg-rate-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
					</image>
				</figure>

			</sidebyside>

		</figure>

		<p>
		If we are considering a specific time <m>t = t^\ast</m>,
		our calculations above say that <em>every</em> average rate calculation for <m>q</m> on a domain containing <m>t^\ast</m> can be converted into a scaled average rate calculation for <m>p</m> on a domain containing <m>a t^\ast</m>,
		since <me> t_1 \le t^\ast \le t_2 \qquad \implies a t_1 \le a t^\ast \le a t_2 </me>.
		Referring back to <xref ref="definition-avg-rate-derivative-value" />,
		since <m>p</m> is assumed to be differentiable,
		<me> p'(a t^\ast) \approx \frac{p(a t_2) - p(a t_1)}{a t_2 - a t_1} </me>,
		where the approximation can be made arbitrarily close by taking <me> a \change{t} = a t_2 - a t_1 </me> sufficiently small.
		If we take <m>\change{t}</m> small enough so that <m>a \change{t}</m> can be described as <q>sufficiently small</q> in this sense,
		then
		<md>
			<mrow> p'(a t^\ast) \amp \approx \frac{p(a t_2) - p(a t_1)}{a t_2 - a t_1}  </mrow>
			<mrow> a p'(a t^\ast) \amp \approx a \cdot \frac{p(a t_2) - p(a t_1)}{a t_2 - a t_1}  </mrow>
			<mrow> a p'(a t^\ast) \amp \approx \slope{q}{t} </mrow>
		</md>,
		satisfying <xref ref="definition-avg-rate-derivative-value" /> for <m>q</m> at <m>t = t^\ast</m>.
		That is,
		<me> q'(t^\ast) = a p'(a t^\ast) </me>,
		as desired.
		</p>

	</proof>

</identity>

<p>
<xref ref="pattern-deriv-h-scale" /> applies equally well when the horizontal scale factor is negative.
Thinking in terms of tangent lines,
if we reflect horizontally then the rise becomes negative because the second point has become the first, and vice versa.
Meanwhile, the <em>amount</em> of run stays the same.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-deriv-tangent-h-reflect">
	<caption> Reflecting a tangent line makes its slope negative. </caption>
	<image width="50%">
		<description>A tangent to a graph and a reflected tangent to a reflected graph.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="deriv.d/h-reflect-tangent.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

</subsection>

</section>


<section>
<title>Calculating derivatives with Sage</title>

<p>
Of course,
Sage can symbolically calculate derivatives.
Here is the syntax for computing a derivative formula in Sage.
<cd><cline>
	derivative(formula, variable)
</cline></cd>
Alternatively,
you can define a function and then apply the <c>derivative</c> method to it.
<cd>
	<cline> q(t) = some_formula </cline>
	<cline> q.derivative() </cline>
</cd>
If you need a specific derivative value,
you can use the <c>substitute</c> method with the first syntax option above.
In the second syntax option,
a function is returned to that can be evaluated with function notation.
<cd>
	<cline> q(t) = some_formula </cline>
	<cline> r = q.derivative() </cline>
	<cline> r(some_number) </cline>
</cd>
</p>

<p> Here is an example using both syntax variations. </p>

<example xml:id="example-deriv-tangent-line">
<title>Using Sage to compute the equation of a tangent line</title>

<p>
Consider function
<me> q(t) = t^3 - 2 t + 5 </me>.
What is the equation of the tangent line to the graph of this function at the point
<me> q(1) = 4 </me>?
It would be tedious to carry this out with pencil-and-paper as we did for a quadratic function in <xref ref="example-deriv-parabolic-motion" />,
so let's use Sage.
</p>

<sage>
	<input>
		var('t')
		dqdt = derivative(t^3 - 2*t + 5, t)
		slope = dqdt.substitute(t = 1)
		print("dqdt =", dqdt)
		print("slope at t=1 is", slope)
	</input>
	<output>
		dqdt = 3*t^2 - 2
		slope at t=1 is 1
	</output>
</sage>

<p>
Now we apply <xref ref="pattern-avg-rate-tangent-line-equation" /> to get tangent line equation
<md>
	<mrow> y \amp = 1 t + (4 - 1 \cdot 1) </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = t + 3 </mrow>
</md>.
</p>

<p>
Here is the same calculation,
but using function notation.
</p>

<sage>
	<input>
		q(t) = t^3 - 2*t + 5
		dqdt = q.derivative()
		slope = dqdt(1)
		line = slope * t + (q(1) - slope * 1)
		print("dqdt is the function")
		print(dqdt)
		print()
		print("slope at t=1 is", slope)
		print()
		print("equation of tangent line at t=1 is")
		print("y =", line)
	</input>
	<output>
		dqdt is the function
		t |--> 3*t^2 - 2

		slope at t=1 is 1

		equation of tangent line at t=1 is
		y = t + 3
	</output>
</sage>

</example>

</section>

